| Lab — Upgrade Path | 1.0ct | E-VVS1 | IGI | ~$450 | ~$960 | Same budget, double the size |

---

## The Half-Carat Trap — Farzana's Take

The magic size premium is real and it's one of the most predictable pricing patterns in the industry. At exactly 0.50ct, 0.75ct, 1.00ct, and 1.50ct, Blue Nile prices jump 10–20% compared to the stone just beneath the threshold.

A 0.49ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent measures 5.1–5.15mm across. A 0.50ct G-VS2 measures 5.2–5.23mm. That is a 0.1mm difference — about the thickness of a piece of paper. Nobody sees this on a ring.

**What buyers actually get for the premium:** A certificate that reads "0.50" instead of "0.49." That's it.

**Farzana's Translation:** I've graded thousands of diamonds and I cannot tell 0.49ct from 0.50ct by eye once they're set. The only person who ever reads the carat weight on a certificate is the insurance company. If the number matters for resale documentation, pay the premium. If it doesn't, save the money and put it toward a better colour grade.

---

## 0.5 Carat Ring Settings — What Blue Nile Offers

The right setting for a half-carat stone should be proportional. Avoid oversized halos that make the diamond look smaller by contrast. Simple solitaires and petite pavé work best.

